---
import SidebarCard from '../components/SidebarCard.astro';
import ClassicShell from '../layouts/ClassicShell.astro';
import { SITE_CONTACT_EMAIL, SITE_DESCRIPTION, SITE_KEYWORDS, SITE_TITLE } from '../consts';
---

<ClassicShell
	title={`${SITE_TITLE} | About`}
	description={SITE_DESCRIPTION}
	pageTitle="About Industrial AI Robots"
	pageIntro="Industrial AI Robots is being built as an English-language robotics reference brand for plant teams, automation buyers, and integrators who need more than surface-level commentary."
	introLabel="About"
	keywords={[...SITE_KEYWORDS, 'about Industrial AI Robots']}
	breadcrumbs={[
		{ name: 'Home', path: '/' },
		{ name: 'About', path: '/about/' },
	]}
>
	<Fragment slot="left-rail">
		<SidebarCard title="Audience" eyebrow="Who It Helps">
			<ul>
				<li>Plant teams exploring where robotics pays off first</li>
				<li>Integrators and technical buyers comparing deployment paths</li>
				<li>Readers sorting through the AI vision and component stack</li>
			</ul>
		</SidebarCard>

		<SidebarCard title="Editorial Bias" eyebrow="What We Favor">
			<p>
				We favor application depth, deployment realism, and content that respects the cost and
				complexity of industrial automation decisions.
			</p>
		</SidebarCard>
	</Fragment>

	<section class="section-block">
		<div class="section-head">
			<div>
				<p class="eyebrow">Editorial Thesis</p>
				<h2>Industrial robotics coverage should start with the use case</h2>
			</div>
		</div>
		<p>
			This site is intended to grow into a premium application-first publication, where ROI logic,
			deployment readiness, and vision-stack decisions all connect. That structure is better for reader
			utility, internal linking, and future commercial value than generic trend coverage.
		</p>
	</section>

	<div class="detail-grid">
		<section class="detail-card">
			<p class="section-kicker">SEO Logic</p>
			<h3>Problems beat buzzwords</h3>
			<p>
				Search value grows when articles speak to inspection, quality, palletizing, line automation,
				and deployment constraints rather than broad robotics hype.
			</p>
		</section>

		<section class="detail-card">
			<p class="section-kicker">Commercial Logic</p>
			<h3>High-value audiences need depth</h3>
			<p>
				OEMs, integrators, and training partners only become a natural fit when the site genuinely
				helps readers move through a meaningful buying and rollout process.
			</p>
		</section>

		<section class="detail-card">
			<p class="section-kicker">Brand Goal</p>
			<h3>Bold, premium, and credible</h3>
			<p>
				The visual language is intentionally more dramatic than a typical industrial blog, but the
				editorial structure stays practical so the site still feels trustworthy.
			</p>
		</section>
	</div>

	<section class="section-block">
		<div class="section-head">
			<div>
				<p class="eyebrow">Planning Surface</p>
				<h2>The long-term framework is visible inside the site</h2>
			</div>
		</div>
		<p>
			The <a href="/topics/">topic map</a> defines the application clusters worth building, while the
			<a href="/methodology/"> methodology page</a> explains how use-case, deployment, and stack pages
			should stay credible over time.
		</p>
	</section>

	<section class="section-block">
		<div class="section-head">
			<div>
				<p class="eyebrow">Reach Out</p>
				<h2>Editorial feedback and future partner fit</h2>
			</div>
		</div>
		<p>
			For corrections, topic ideas, or future partnership conversations, email <a href={`mailto:${SITE_CONTACT_EMAIL}`}>{SITE_CONTACT_EMAIL}</a>.
			The current priority is building a deeper use-case library first so any later sponsor inventory is supported by real authority.
		</p>
	</section>
</ClassicShell>
